VL  - 24
IS  - 3
SP  - 455
EP  - 470
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/11/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(89)90032-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393289900329
AB  - The information used by researchers in cross-equation tests of rational expectations may be a small subset of the information available to the market. Such tests produce consistent estimates, but have low power. We develop a mechanism for dealing with this problem and use the procedure to perform cross-equation tests on predictions from the football betting market. The tests fail to reject rationality. We provide evidence that market predictions from betting markets are not formed rationally. It appears, therefore, that cross-equation tests have low power even if the information sets used by the researcher and the market are approximately the same.
